#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic &vmguest; management"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:15
#, no-c-format
msgid "Most management tasks, such as starting or stopping a &vmguest;, can either be done using the graphical application &vmm; or on the command line using <command>virsh</command> . Connecting to the graphical console via VNC is only possible from a graphical user interface."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:22
#, no-c-format
msgid "Managing &vmguest;s on a remote &vmhost;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:23
#, no-c-format
msgid "If started on a &vmhost;, the &libvirt; tools &vmm;, <command>virsh</command> , and <command>virt-viewer</command> can be used to manage &vmguest;s on the host. However, it is also possible to manage &vmguest;s on a remote &vmhost;. This requires configuring remote access for &libvirt; on the host. For instructions, see <xref linkend=\"cha-libvirt-connect\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:31
#, no-c-format
msgid "To connect to such a remote host with &vmm;, you need to set up a connection as explained in <xref linkend=\"sec-libvirt-connect-connecting-vmm\"/> . If connecting to a remote host using <command>virsh</command> or <command>virt-viewer</command> , you need to specify a connection URI with the parameter <option>-c</option> (for example, <command>virsh -c qemu+tls://&wsIIIname;/system</command> or <command>virsh -c xen+ssh://</command> ). The form of connection URI depends on the connection type and the hypervisor&mdash;see <xref linkend=\"sec-libvirt-connect-connecting\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:42
#, no-c-format
msgid "Examples in this chapter are all listed without a connection URI."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:47
#, no-c-format
msgid "Listing &vmguest;s"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:49
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &vmguest; listing shows all &vmguest;s managed by &libvirt; on a &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:55
#, no-c-format
msgid "Listing &vmguest;s with &vmm;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:56
#, no-c-format
msgid "The main window of the &vmm; lists all &vmguest;s for each &vmhost; it is connected to. Each &vmguest; entry contains the machine's name, its status ( <guimenu>Running</guimenu> , <guimenu>Paused</guimenu> , or <guimenu>Shutoff</guimenu> ) displayed as an icon and literally, and a CPU usage bar."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Listing &vmguest;s with <command>virsh</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:67
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use the command <command>virsh</command> <option>list</option> to get a list of &vmguest;s:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:73
#, no-c-format
msgid "List all running guests"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: listitem
#: libvirt_managing.xml:74
#, no-c-format
msgid "<screen>&prompt.user;virsh list</screen>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:79
#, no-c-format
msgid "List all running and inactive guests"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: listitem
#: libvirt_managing.xml:80
#, no-c-format
msgid "<screen>&prompt.user;virsh list --all</screen>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:85
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information and further options, see <command>virsh help list</command> or <command>man 1 virsh</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:92
#, no-c-format
msgid "Accessing the &vmguest; via console"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:94
#, no-c-format
msgid "&vmguest;s can be accessed via a VNC connection (graphical console) or, if supported by the guest operating system, via a serial console."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:100
#, no-c-format
msgid "Opening a graphical console"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:101
#, no-c-format
msgid "Opening a graphical console to a &vmguest; lets you interact with the machine like a physical host via a VNC connection. If accessing the VNC server requires authentication, you are prompted to enter a user name (if applicable) and a password."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:107
#, no-c-format
msgid "When you click into the VNC console, the cursor is <quote>grabbed</quote> and cannot be used outside the console anymore. To release it, press <keycombo> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap function=\"control\"/> </keycombo> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:114
#, no-c-format
msgid "Seamless (absolute) cursor movement"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:115
#, no-c-format
msgid "To prevent the console from grabbing the cursor and to enable seamless cursor movement, add a tablet input device to the &vmguest;. See <xref linkend=\"sec-libvirt-config-input\"/> for more information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:121
#, no-c-format
msgid "Certain key combinations such as <keycombo> <keycap function=\"control\"/> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap function=\"delete\"/> </keycombo> are interpreted by the host system and are not passed to the &vmguest;. To pass such key combinations to a &vmguest;, open the <guimenu>Send Key</guimenu> menu from the VNC window and choose the desired key combination entry. The <guimenu>Send Key</guimenu> menu is only available when using &vmm; and <command>virt-viewer</command> . With &vmm;, you can alternatively use the <quote>sticky key</quote> feature as explained in <xref linkend=\"tip-libvirt-inst-vmm-sticky\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:133
#, no-c-format
msgid "Supported VNC viewers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:134
#, no-c-format
msgid "Principally all VNC viewers can connect to the console of a &vmguest;. However, if you are using SASL authentication and/or TLS/SSL connection to access the guest, the options are limited. Common VNC viewers such as <command>tightvnc</command> or <command>tigervnc</command> support neither SASL authentication nor TLS/SSL. The only supported alternative to &vmm; and <command>virt-viewer</command> is Remmina (refer to <xref linkend=\"vnc-remmina\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid "Opening a graphical console with &vmm;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:153
#, no-c-format
msgid "Choose <guimenu>Open</guimenu> from the pop-up menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:160
#, no-c-format
msgid "Opening a graphical console with <command>virt-viewer</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:161
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>virt-viewer</command> is a simple VNC viewer with added functionality for displaying &vmguest; consoles. For example, it can be started in <quote>wait</quote> mode, where it waits for a &vmguest; to start before it connects. It also supports automatically reconnecting to a &vmguest; that is rebooted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>virt-viewer</command> addresses &vmguest;s by name, by ID or by UUID. Use <command>virsh</command> <option>list --all</option> to get this data."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid "To connect to a guest that is running or paused, use either the ID, UUID, or name. &vmguest;s that are shut off do not have an ID&mdash;you can only connect to them by UUID or name."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:180
#, no-c-format
msgid "Connect to guest with the ID <literal>8</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: listitem
#: libvirt_managing.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid "<screen>&prompt.user;virt-viewer 8</screen>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:186
#, no-c-format
msgid "Connect to the inactive guest named <literal>sles12</literal> ; the connection window will open once the guest starts"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:188
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virt-viewer --wait sles12"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:189
#, no-c-format
msgid "With the <option>--wait</option> option, the connection will be upheld even if the &vmguest; is not running at the moment. When the guest starts, the viewer will be launched."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:197
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information, see <command>virt-viewer</command> <option>--help</option> or <command>man 1 virt-viewer</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:202
#, no-c-format
msgid "Password input on remote connections with SSH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:203
#, no-c-format
msgid "When using <command>virt-viewer</command> to open a connection to a remote host via SSH, the SSH password needs to be entered twice. The first time for authenticating with &libvirt;, the second time for authenticating with the VNC server. The second password needs to be provided on the command line where virt-viewer was started."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:215
#, no-c-format
msgid "Opening a serial console"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid "Accessing the graphical console of a virtual machine requires a graphical environment on the client accessing the &vmguest;. As an alternative, virtual machines managed with libvirt can also be accessed from the shell via the serial console and <command>virsh</command> . To open a serial console to a &vmguest; named <quote>sles12</quote> , run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:224
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh console sles12"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:225
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>virsh console</command> takes two optional flags: <option>--safe</option> ensures exclusive access to the console, <option>--force</option> disconnects any existing sessions before connecting. Both features need to be supported by the guest operating system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "Being able to connect to a &vmguest; via serial console requires that the guest operating system supports serial console access and is properly supported. Refer to the guest operating system manual for more information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:238
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enabling serial console access for &sle; and &opensuse; guests"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:239
#, no-c-format
msgid "Serial console access in &sle; and &opensuse; is disabled by default. To enable it, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:245
#, no-c-format
msgid "&slsa; 12 and up/&opensuse;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:247
#, no-c-format
msgid "Launch the &yast; Boot Loader module and switch to the <guimenu>Kernel Parameters</guimenu> tab. Add <literal>console=ttyS0</literal> to the field <guimenu>Optional Kernel Command Line Parameter</guimenu> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:255
#, no-c-format
msgid "&slsa; 11"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid "Launch the &yast; Boot Loader module and select the boot entry for which to activate serial console access. Choose <guimenu>Edit</guimenu> and add <literal>console=ttyS0</literal> to the field <guimenu>Optional Kernel Command Line Parameter</guimenu> . Additionally, edit <filename>/etc/inittab</filename> and uncomment the line with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:265
#, no-c-format
msgid "#S0:12345:respawn:/sbin/agetty -L 9600 ttyS0 vt102"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:273
#, no-c-format
msgid "Changing a &vmguest;'s state: start, stop, pause"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:275
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting, stopping or pausing a &vmguest; can be done with either &vmm; or <command>virsh</command> . You can also configure a &vmguest; to be automatically started when booting the &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:281
#, no-c-format
msgid "When shutting down a &vmguest;, you may either shut it down gracefully, or force the shutdown. The latter is equivalent to pulling the power plug on a physical host and is only recommended if there are no alternatives. Forcing a shutdown may cause file system corruption and loss of data on the &vmguest;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:291
#, no-c-format
msgid "To be able to perform a graceful shutdown, the &vmguest; must be configured to support <xref linkend=\"gloss-vt-acpi\"/> . If you have created the guest with the &vmm;, ACPI should be available in the &vmguest;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "Depending on the guest operating system, availability of ACPI may not be sufficient to perform a graceful shutdown. It is strongly recommended to test shutting down and rebooting a guest before using it in production. &opensuse; or &sled;, for example, can require &pk; authorization for shutdown and reboot. Make sure this policy is turned off on all &vmguest;s."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:303
#, no-c-format
msgid "If ACPI was enabled during a Windows XP/Windows Server 2003 guest installation, turning it on in the &vmguest; configuration only is not sufficient. For more information, see:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid "<link xlink:href=\"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/kb/314088\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:315
#, no-c-format
msgid "<link xlink:href=\"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/kb/309283\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:320
#, no-c-format
msgid "Regardless of the &vmguest;'s configuration, a graceful shutdown is always possible from within the guest operating system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
