#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:456
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving and restoring the state of a &vmguest;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:458
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving a &vmguest; preserves the exact state of the guest’s memory. The operation is similar to <emphasis>hibernating</emphasis> a computer. A saved &vmguest; can be quickly restored to its previously saved running condition."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:464
#, no-c-format
msgid "When saved, the &vmguest; is paused, its current memory state is saved to disk, and then the guest is stopped. The operation does not make a copy of any portion of the &vmguest;’s virtual disk. The amount of time taken to save the virtual machine depends on the amount of memory allocated. When saved, a &vmguest;’s memory is returned to the pool of memory available on the &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:473
#, no-c-format
msgid "The restore operation loads a &vmguest;’s previously saved memory state file and starts it. The guest is not booted but instead resumed at the point where it was previously saved. The operation is similar to coming out of hibernation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &vmguest; is saved to a state file. Make sure there is enough space on the partition you are going to save to. For an estimation of the file size in megabytes to be expected, issue the following command on the guest:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:486
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;free -mh | awk '/^Mem:/ {print $3}'"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always restore saved guests"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:490
#, no-c-format
msgid "After using the save operation, do not boot or start the saved &vmguest;. Doing so would cause the machine's virtual disk and the saved memory state to get out of synchronization. This can result in critical errors when restoring the guest."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:496
#, no-c-format
msgid "To be able to work with a saved &vmguest; again, use the restore operation. If you used <command>virsh</command> to save a &vmguest;, you cannot restore it using &vmm;. In this case, make sure to restore using <command>virsh</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:505
#, no-c-format
msgid "Synchronize &vmguest;'s time after restoring it"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:506
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you restore the &vmguest; after a long pause (hours) since it was saved, its time synchronization service&mdash;for example, &chronyd;&mdash;may refuse to synchronize its time. In this case, manually synchronize &vmguest;'s time. For example, for &kvm; hosts, you can use the &qemu; guest agent and instruct the guest with the <command>guest-set-time</command> . Refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-qemu-ga\"/> for more details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid "Only for &vmguest;s with disk types <literal>raw</literal> , <literal>qcow2</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:519
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving and restoring &vmguest;s is only possible if the &vmguest; is using a virtual disk of the type <literal>raw</literal> ( <filename>.img</filename> ), or <emphasis>qcow2</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:527
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving/restoring with &vmm;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:529
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving a &vmguest;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:531
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open a VNC connection window to a &vmguest;. Make sure the guest is running."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:537
#, no-c-format
msgid "Choose <menuchoice> <guimenu>Virtual Machine</guimenu> <guimenu>Shutdown</guimenu> <guimenu>Save</guimenu> </menuchoice> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restoring a &vmguest;"
msgstr ""

