#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:594
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating and managing snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:596
#, no-c-format
msgid "&vmguest; snapshots are snapshots of the complete virtual machine including the state of CPU, RAM, devices, and the content of all writable disks. To use virtual machine snapshots, all the attached hard disks need to use the qcow2 disk image format, and at least one of them needs to be writable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots let you restore the state of the machine at a particular point in time. This is useful when undoing a faulty configuration or the installation of a lot of packages. After starting a snapshot that was created while the &vmguest; was shut off, you will need to boot it. Any changes written to the disk after that point in time will be lost when starting the snapshot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:612
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots are supported on &kvm; &vmhost;s only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:618
#, no-c-format
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:619
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are several specific terms used to describe the types of snapshots:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:624
#, no-c-format
msgid "Internal snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:626
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots that are saved into the qcow2 file of the original &vmguest;. The file holds both the saved state of the snapshot and the changes made since the snapshot was taken. The main advantage of internal snapshots is that they are all stored in one file and therefore it is easy to copy or move them across multiple machines."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:636
#, no-c-format
msgid "External snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:638
#, no-c-format
msgid "When creating an external snapshot, the original qcow2 file is saved and made read-only, while a new qcow2 file is created to hold the changes. The original file is sometimes called a 'backing' or 'base' file, while the new file with all the changes is called an 'overlay' or 'derived' file. External snapshots are useful when performing backups of &vmguest;s. However, external snapshots are not supported by &vmm;, and cannot be deleted by <command>virsh</command> directly. For more information on external snapshots in &qemu;, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-qemu-guest-inst-qemu-img-effect\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:652
#, no-c-format
msgid "Live snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:654
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots created when the original &vmguest; is running. Internal live snapshots support saving the devices, and memory and disk states, while external live snapshots with <command>virsh</command> support saving either the memory state, or the disk state, or both."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:663
#, no-c-format
msgid "Offline snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:665
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots created from a &vmguest; that is shut off. This ensures data integrity as all the guest's processes are stopped and no memory is in use."
msgstr ""

